reviews.review_text: Not Bad Pretty good but not quite as good as earlier years !

major highlight from '86 i know that this is '86, but this is a strong show.  the crazy fingers is sweet with full bass, the he's gone->smokestack is slinky and unique sounding to this year.

the drumz is what got me "turned on" to drumz in a big way.  in '87, this righteous collector from oaklahoma mailed my sister a copy.  i couldn't get enough of the intricate rhythms and mickey's beam.  it's truly sublime.

at the time, it was the crispest board that i had.  now, i'm spoiled with that good sound.  this one is excellent but still doesn't have the warmth and clarity of the copy from oakie-aiko (and that's on a D-90 from '87!).  there are definitely MANY cassette generations here.  either that or there were some patch problems as there is a strong hiss.

the post-drums is hot.  though the other one has the quiet intro, when phil kicks in, he kicks right in!   an '85 or '86 comes a time is always welcome, though little can compare to 11-1-85.

mmmm-bop, bop-bop.
